               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1804" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1804" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1804" type="surname" value="SHREEVE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1804" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY SHREEVE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and live in Seymour-place, Maryle<lb></lb>bone. I am the mother of Elizabeth Bailey—I remember her being mar<lb></lb>ried to the prisoner at the parish church of St. Mary Magdalen, Bermond<lb></lb>sey, on the 5th of January, 1816—I was present, and witnessed it—I saw my daughter yesterday.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183902040271"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. Did they continue to live together? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, but not in my house—I heard of his second wife going to live with them, but I never saw her there—I know nothing of the second marriage.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1805" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1805" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1805" type="surname" value="BRADFIELD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1805" type="given" value="DEBORAH"></interp>DEBORAH BRADFIELD</persName>
                  </hi>. I was married to the prisoner on the 12th of June last, at the parish church of St. Mary, Newington.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You were married by banns? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I had been living at the prisoner's two months before—his wife lived in the same house—I knew he had a wife—I was in the family-way by him, and it was proposed that we should marry, that the child should be legitimate, and that I might get a situation as wet nurse if I could show my marriage<lb></lb>register—his wife knew of it—I had no wish to prosecute him.</p>
